1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,038
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:26,557 --> 00:00:31,204
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,729 --> 00:00:39,076
The word I'd like to tackle this evening is hetu.

4
00:00:40,398 --> 00:00:44,262
It means root and the roots of our suffering.

5
00:00:45,542 --> 00:00:50,292
And it's really, I suppose, what you would call these days our depth psychology.

6
00:00:51,515 --> 00:00:58,328
And it splits into three roots, which won't come as a surprise to you.

7
00:00:59,930 --> 00:01:02,314
Greed, hatred and delusion.

8
00:01:04,058 --> 00:01:06,302
The word for greed is lobe here.

9
00:01:07,245 --> 00:01:07,364
Greed.

10
00:01:07,834 --> 00:01:11,838
Most of you would know perhaps the word tanha, which means desire.

11
00:01:12,959 --> 00:01:17,924
But lobha is that attitude that's translated as greed.

12
00:01:18,445 --> 00:01:22,971
But I think it's much better to understand it as acquisitiveness.

13
00:01:24,731 --> 00:01:25,632
Acquisitiveness.

14
00:01:27,355 --> 00:01:35,022
And the second one is dosa, which means just aversion, not wanting.

15
00:01:36,352 --> 00:01:38,796
And the third one, moha, is delusion.

16
00:01:39,798 --> 00:01:44,525
Now we've come across the word avijja, which means ignorance.

17
00:01:44,546 --> 00:01:51,957
It's translated as ignorance, but actually it's far better translated in a very neutral sense of just not knowing.

18
00:01:53,019 --> 00:01:58,007
And then we make this mistake, and that mistake we call our delusions.

19
00:01:59,319 --> 00:02:13,521
So the mistake, of course, is to believe ourselves to be phenomenal psychophysical organisms, human beings, which is understandable.

20
00:02:13,542 --> 00:02:24,198
I mean, our consciousness moves into the cellular life of the fetus, and when it's born, what does it know, apart from what it's experiencing?

21
00:02:24,558 --> 00:02:25,259
No, it's not.

22
00:02:25,830 --> 00:02:34,007
It's not something to be... You can't expect anything else except for that consciousness to say, well, this is what I am.

23
00:02:34,206 --> 00:02:43,104
This is what I... Not actually saying it intellectually, but just a direct relationship with what it experiences as being me.

24
00:02:45,870 --> 00:02:46,371
And...

25
00:02:48,157 --> 00:02:49,799
And this is what we call the self.

26
00:02:49,878 --> 00:02:55,224
So the self isn't a thing, it's not an object, it's a relationship.

27
00:02:55,564 --> 00:02:58,688
It's a relationship we have to what we experience.

28
00:02:58,709 --> 00:03:00,610
This is me or mine.

29
00:03:01,170 --> 00:03:08,620
So there's your basic position in the world which we call delusive, a delusion, moha.

30
00:03:10,140 --> 00:03:14,205
So this is me and these things are mine.

31
00:03:15,606 --> 00:03:17,269
So identity and possessions.

32
00:03:18,616 --> 00:03:26,899
So now you can see that once you've established that sort of relationship with the world, there's a whole load of things which aren't me, aren't mine.

33
00:03:28,201 --> 00:03:32,895
And that's where the barrier comes.

34
00:03:34,698 --> 00:03:53,399
Underlying, remember, the sense of self, and this is really quite an important understanding, is that the self actually in itself, or we in ourselves, never truly believe in the self itself.

35
00:03:55,061 --> 00:04:03,591
And the way that expresses itself is through a constant anxiety of being in control of

36
00:04:04,582 --> 00:04:07,247
of our lives, of our things and so on.

37
00:04:09,290 --> 00:04:19,990
If the self were actually rock hard, if it were a real rock hard self, which was immutable and eternal, then obviously that wouldn't happen.

38
00:04:20,690 --> 00:04:27,502
It's just that there's somewhere inside us that knows that this relationship doesn't quite fit, isn't quite right.

39
00:04:28,764 --> 00:04:33,911
And so we're constantly trying to acquire the future.

40
00:04:34,230 --> 00:04:37,375
And that's what lobe means, I suppose, in its deepest sense.

41
00:04:38,435 --> 00:04:40,497
We're trying to control the future.

42
00:04:41,779 --> 00:04:47,185
And to do that, you've got to, of course, get rid of anything that upsets your presumed future.

43
00:04:48,166 --> 00:04:58,197
So your attitude, our attitude to life, is always this trying to make sure that things are going to go the way I want them to.

44
00:04:58,550 --> 00:05:01,156
And if anything gets in the way then I want to get rid of it.

45
00:05:02,259 --> 00:05:05,507
Simple as that.

46
00:05:05,526 --> 00:05:10,720
And it comes down into the moment as holding on to what we have.

47
00:05:11,509 --> 00:05:14,271
and defending it from the enemy.

48
00:05:15,112 --> 00:05:17,776
And the enemy is simply all those who want what we have.

49
00:05:18,375 --> 00:05:18,937
Very simple.

50
00:05:21,399 --> 00:05:39,475
So once we recognize that mechanism, you see, and we know it's coming from this deeper delusion, this deeper mistake we've made of presuming that this is what we are, then our challenge is to be aware of that.

51
00:05:40,838 --> 00:05:42,639
I mean, that's what the vipassana is about.

52
00:05:43,581 --> 00:05:49,788
It's leading us to the awareness of every time the mind is holding on to something or pushing something away.

53
00:05:49,827 --> 00:06:02,262
And what we find is that just to be aware of it allows us just a small space of freedom.

54
00:06:03,882 --> 00:06:06,927
And the freedom is not to act according to those impulses.

55
00:06:07,627 --> 00:06:08,988
That's where the liberation is.

56
00:06:10,353 --> 00:06:16,954
But these roots, so they're roots, they're deep within our psychology, are so...

57
00:06:17,625 --> 00:06:42,047
deeply rooted that we're not aware we're not aware of how of how we're so afraid of letting go so afraid of of just living as it were in the moment and making the decisions in the moment with the faith that things evolve and if things happen that we don't want to happen then

58
00:06:42,415 --> 00:06:54,687
then that's also part of our evolution, that we can't stop things happening which are against us, because we live in a world that we can't control.

59
00:07:01,415 --> 00:07:09,502
So the trick is to be aware of how the mind is constantly wanting to control

60
00:07:11,002 --> 00:07:24,692
Therefore it doesn't listen, it doesn't really see the way things are, the way things really are, and it constantly finds itself in this little conflict, this conflict with the world as it is.

61
00:07:26,214 --> 00:07:28,420
Even a simple thing like opening the gate.

62
00:07:29,327 --> 00:07:33,072
I was out there the other day, and for some reason it wouldn't open.

63
00:07:33,632 --> 00:07:35,555
So I found myself getting irritated with it.

64
00:07:35,576 --> 00:07:39,540
The gate should open when I want it to open, in the way that I want it to open.

65
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:41,043
I just refused to do so.

66
00:07:42,204 --> 00:07:48,531
Even the slightest things, you'll catch the irritation, you'll catch the grabbing, you'll catch the desire.

67
00:07:49,894 --> 00:07:54,879
And the more we don't act on those impulses...

68
00:07:55,889 --> 00:08:01,418
the more we're challenging that deep delusion that we have of who we are.

69
00:08:02,119 --> 00:08:07,767
And the more we do that, the more we come across this anxiety, this sort of deep-seated fear.

70
00:08:08,809 --> 00:08:10,291
And it's not a place we like to be.

71
00:08:10,331 --> 00:08:11,954
It's not a place we like to be at all.

72
00:08:12,654 --> 00:08:14,497
We don't like to be in a state of don't know.

73
00:08:14,517 --> 00:08:18,764
And it's getting used to that.

74
00:08:18,845 --> 00:08:23,432
It's getting used to the fear that surrounds that, the anxiety that surrounds that.

75
00:08:24,694 --> 00:08:33,885
And once we're used to that, to those feelings and how it feels to be like that, then we've already distanced from it.

76
00:08:37,850 --> 00:08:48,384
And what we realize has been a great prevention for us to actually dig deep is the fear of that fear, the fear of that anxiety.

77
00:08:49,306 --> 00:08:51,207
And just bounce off it, just pull off it quick.

78
00:08:52,690 --> 00:09:06,327
And by making fear itself an object and getting used to the feelings of fear, used to the feelings of anxiety, and this fear of it disappears, or begins to disappear, or at least diminishes.

79
00:09:08,070 --> 00:09:12,235
And of course, once we lose the fear of fear, what is there to frighten us?

80
00:09:14,258 --> 00:09:14,378
Right?

81
00:09:19,437 --> 00:09:22,861
So this is the Buddha's deep psychology, really.

82
00:09:23,623 --> 00:09:31,313
From then on, it moves into how it manifests through daily life through the dependent wheel of origination.

83
00:09:32,556 --> 00:09:37,142
The wheel of dependent origination, which is also a dependent wheel.

84
00:09:43,028 --> 00:09:43,971
So I can only hope.

85
00:09:44,491 --> 00:09:46,356
My words have been of some assistance.

86
00:09:46,999 --> 00:09:58,489
May you be liberated in this very lifetime, sooner rather than later.

